at this single plant and the peoples who domesticated it came to be inextricably entangled with one another over the past nine millennia. Tracing maize from its first appearance and domestication in ancient campsites and settlements in Mexico to its intercontinental journey through most of North and South America, this history also tells the story of the artistic creativity, technological prowess, and social, political, and economic resilience of America’s first peoples.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Archaeology.2bisacsh  aagriculture in the americas.  aarcheobotany.  acash crop.  acorn production.  acorn.  acrop science.  aeat corn.  afood and agriculture.  afood crops.  afood production.  afood science.  aglobal agriculture.  aglobal economies.  aglobal food source.  agrowing corn.  agrowing food.  ahistory of agriculture.  ahistory of corn.  ahistory of food.  ahistory of maize.  aindustrial agriculture.  ainternational reliance on corn.  amaize production.  amexican agriculture.  asocial science.  aworldwide food production.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z97831106211120 cprintz978052027687140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052096169240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520961692423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520961692/original  a978-3-11-062111-2  University of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY